 that drove its creation encompassed not only local politicians but also banks, credit rating firms, insurance companies, and the national municipal bond market. Moving between the local and the national, The Bonds of Inequality uncovers how racial inequalities in San Francisco were intrinsically tied to municipal finance arrangements and how these arrangements were central in determining the distribution of resources in the city. By homing in on financing and its imperatives, Jenkins boldly rewrites the history of modern American cities, revealing the hidden strings that bind debt and power, race and inequity, democracy and capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDebts, PubliczCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aEqualityxEconomic aspectszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aFinance, PubliczCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aFinance, Public-History-California-San Francisco-20th century. 0aMunicipal bondszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMunicipal bonds-History-California-San Francisco-20th century. 0aMunicipal governmentzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxFinancexHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismxEconomic aspectszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  adebt, infrastructure, finance, capitalism, racism, democracy, urban politics, African Americans, welfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226721682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226721682/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles